  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a lived reality for many of us in the tech field. As a software developer who moved from another country and now lives in Washington DC, I've seen how the fear of confirming negative stereotypes about one's group can undermine performance. When students from underrepresented backgrounds are told they're 'not good at math,' or when women are reminded that they're 'less capable in engineering,' it doesn't just affect their confidence—it directly impacts their ability to think clearly and solve problems. My own depression, which has been a constant companion since I was younger, makes me acutely aware of how stress can cloud judgment. In a field where precision and focus are critical, stereotype threat isn't just an issue—it's a barrier to progress. We absolutely must address it. The key isn't just awareness but creating environments where people feel safe to make mistakes. I've seen this in my part-time work with local coding clubs for immigrants and refugees—when we remove the pressure to perform perfectly and focus on learning, participation increases dramatically. It’s about building psychological safety, not just changing policies. For me, this means mentoring younger developers from diverse backgrounds, helping them see that their worth isn't tied to their ability to be 'perfect' in the moment. Addressing stereotype threat requires consistent effort, empathy, and a shift in how we view success in STEM. It's not about fixing the problem but helping people feel valued for who they are, not just what they can do.",
